/target
*.db
*.db-wal
*.db-shm
# private memory snapshots must never be committed (they hold real memories)
*.jsonl
tools/__pycache__/
# the real Guard rulebook holds machine/business internals (NAS IP, hosts,
# container names) - keep it local; a redacted .example is tracked instead.
guard-rulebook.json

# response Guard rulebook (Stop-hook, capability-amnesia) - keep local, .example is tracked
guard-response-rulebook.json
# The committed drift-eval corpus is SYNTHETIC (no real memories) - the only
# jsonl that belongs in the repo.
!eval/drift_scenarios.jsonl

# Measurement corpora and their outputs. These are built FROM a live store, so a
# gold body is a real memory, an entity id names a real project, and a per-item
# dump carries both. They live in the per-user data directory and belong nowhere
# near a public repo - but the eval harness reads and writes files by name, so it
# is one careless copy into eval/ away from being staged by `git add -A`. Deny by
# name rather than trusting that nobody will ever put one here.
#
# Inside eval/ the default flips: deny every json and name the one exception.
# A name-based list only stops the names someone thought of, and the harness lets
# you choose any output name you like (`--out <file>`), so eval/ needs the
# catch-all. drift_noise_baseline.json is a committed one-way ratchet.
/eval/*.json
!/eval/drift_noise_baseline.json

# Outside eval/ a catch-all would be wrong, so deny by name instead - these are
# what the harness produces when it is run from the crate root.
golds*.json
percategory_queries*.json
queries*.json
items*.json
strata*.json
scores*.json
hits*.json
*_hits.json
thor-src-*.tar.gz
*.npy
